07915nam a22010935i 9783110421453DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018935090  a97831104214537 a10.1515/97831104214532doi  a(DE-B1597)451146  a(OCoLC)1054067406  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBL785b.W36 2018 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a292.1/3223  aNH 5250qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/125678:00aWandering Myths :bTranscultural Uses of Myth in the Ancient World /ced. by Beate Dignas, Lucy Gaynor Audley-Miller. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (LIV, 427 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface. Wandering Myths: Transcultural Uses of Myth in the Ancient World -- tIntroduction. Travelling Myths, Travelling Heroes -- tPart I: Changing Cultural and Mythical Landscapes in Anatolia -- tKingship in Heaven in Anatolia, Syria and Greece. Patterns of Convergence and Divergence -- tMaking Meaning of Myth. On the Interpretation of Mythological Imagery in the Polyxena Sarcophagus and the Kızılbel Tomb and the History of Achaemenid Asia Minor -- tMyth, Memory and the Past. Wandering Heroes between Arcadia and Cyprus -- tPart II: Reception and Innovation of Mythological Programmes between Greece and Italy -- tFrom Mezntie to Mezentius? The Stratigraphy of a Myth in Etruria and Rome -- tPots, Plots, and Performance. Comic and Tragic Iconography in Apulian Vase Painting -- tDistributed Narrative. A Very Short History of Juxtaposing Myths on Pompeian Walls -- tNo One is Immortal. From Exemplum Mortalitatis to Exemplum Virtutis -- tAttic Sarcophagi. Myth Selection and the Heroising Tradition -- tPart III: Wandering East, Wandering South -- tGilgāmeš and Homer: The Missing Link? -- tMyth, Memory, and Mimesis. The Inaros Cycle as Literature of Resistance -- tDeath on the Nile: The Myth of Osiris and the Utility of History in Diodorus. Egypt In Greco-Roman Historiography -- tWandering Hero, Wandering Myths? The Image of Heracles in Iran -- tThe Transformations of Achilles on Late Roman Mosaics in the East -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn spite of the growing amount of important new work being carried out on uses of myth in particular ancient contexts, their appeal and reception beyond the framework of one culture have rarely been the primary object of enquiry in contemporary debate. Highlighting the fact that ancient societies were linked by their shared use of mythological narratives, Wandering Myths aims to advance our understanding of the mechanisms by which such tales were disseminated cross-culturally and to investigate how they gained local resonances. In order to assess both wider geographic circulations and to explore specific local features and interpretations, a regional approach is adopted, with a particular focus on Anatolia, the Near East and Italy. Contributions are drawn from a range of disciplines, and cross a wide chronological span, but all are interlinked by their engagement with questions focusing on the factors that guided the processes of reception and steered the facets of local interpretation. The Preface and Epilogue evaluate the material in a synoptic way and frame the challenging questions and views expressed in the Introduction.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aMythology, Greek. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aCross-cultural approach.  aadaptation of myth.  amechanisms of dissemination.  atransformation of heroes.1 aAudley-Miller, Lucy Gaynor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAudley-Miller, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4h